
    ANC MP Mervyn Dirks who is facing expulsion from Parliament has apologised unreservedly showing a middle finger at a female colleague.Dirks denied the allegations that he had threatened the female MP.He was thrown out for raising his middle finger and allegedly making threats against a female colleague during a Parliamentary session last week Wednesday.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=1240447880&t=artid%3d733f1a8a-e5d7-432b-aabd-984206bf71dc%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=1240447880&t=artid%3d733f1a8a-e5d7-432b-aabd-984206bf71dc%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>The House chairperson Cedric Frolick suspended proceedings to sort out the chamber's electronic voting system on the day.Meanwhile, when the proceedings resumed, DA chief whip John Steenhuisen rose on a point of order and said just before the House adjourned he had seen Dirks attempt to strike one of the female members sitting next to him.Speaking to THE WITNESS, ANC Chief Whip Jackson Mthembu, said it is unacceptable that a member of Parliament can be found to be involved in such unbecoming behaviour. "Dirks’s behaviour was despicable and not in keeping with the image of Parliament,” said Mthembu.
